docs.text: hong kong cinema has been going through a bad spell .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the last few productions have been effect laded action adventures that combine both the best and worst of american filmmaking with the same qualities of hong kong films .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: in a nutshell , the current crop of films from hong kong has been maddeningly convoluted and visually sumptuous .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: with the one time british colony reverting back to mainland ownership , a lot of hong kong's best talents have crossed the pacific to work on u . s . productions .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: such talents as jackie chan ( rush hour ) , chow yun-fat ( anna & the king , the corrupter ) and yuen woo-ping ( the matrix ) have all moved into the budget bloated world of hollywood filmmaking with mixed results .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: now we can add two other hong kong filmmakers to the mix with star jet li and director and fight choreographer corey yuen kwai .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: unfortunately " romeo must die " bears all the trademarks of a typical hollywood action film and none of hong kong's rhythms .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the film opens in a nightclub as an asian couple is necking .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: enter a group of chinese gangsters led by kai sing ( russell wong ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: kai confronts po sing ( jon kit lee ) , the son of kai's boss and leader of the local chinese family .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: a battle breaks out between the bodyguards of the club and kai , who handily kicks and punches his opponents down .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it's not until club owner silk ( rapper dmx ) , bears down on kai and his henchmen that the fight ends .

docs.text: the following morning po sing is found dead .

docs.text: his concern that the war between his and the chinese family may explode and ruin his plans to move out of the business of corruption and into a legitimate venture .

docs.text: issac implores his chief of security , mac ( issiah washington ) to watch after his son and daughter .

docs.text: he fights with the guards and is dragged off to be disciplined .

docs.text: escaping to the u . s . han sets out to find the person responsible for his brother's death .

docs.text: " romeo must die " is in many ways a fun film .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it is both absurd and assured .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the basic plot of a gangster wanting to become legitimate echoes " the godfather " .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the relationship between jet li's han and aaliyah's trish o'day reminds us of abel ferrera's " china girl " , except that romeo must die's couple never once exchange more than a loving glance towards one another .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: their romance is much more puritanical than any other romance in film history .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the performances are adequate if not fully acceptable .

docs.text: li , of course has the showiest part , having to express both an innocents and steadfast determination .

docs.text: allayah , in her feature film debut manages to carry what little is asked of her with a certain style and grace .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it's obvious that the camera loves her and she is very photogenic .

docs.text: but , still the part is under written in such a way that even a poor performance would not have affected it .

docs.text: delro lindo as issac o'day carries himself well in the film .

docs.text: an unsung and under appreciated actor , mr . lindo turns out the films best performance .

docs.text: the other performers are all adequate in what the script asks of them except for d . b . woodside as issac's son , colin .

docs.text: the performance is undirected , with the character changing his tone and demeanor in accordance with whatever location he is in .

docs.text: an unfocused performance that should have been reigned in and / or better written .

docs.text: first time director andrzej bartkowiak does a workmanlike job in handling the film .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: having a career as one of the industry's best cinematographers , bartkiwiak knows how to set up his shots , and " romeo must die " does look good .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: but the pacing of the film is lethargic , only coming to a semblance of life during the fight scenes .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the script by eric bernt and john jarrell is not focused in such a way that we can care about the characters or the situations they are in .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the big gambit of buying up waterfront property to facilitate the building of a sports center for a nfl team is needlessly confusing .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: and of course the common practice of one character being the comic relief of the film becomes painfully obvious here as anthony anderson as allayah's bodyguard , maurice has no comic timing whatsoever .

docs.text: the best things about the film are its fight scenes .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: jet li is a master of these intricate physical battles .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: one needs only to see his film " fist of legend " to understand that the man is without peer in the realm of martial art combat .

docs.text: here , jet is given the opportunity to show off in a way that " lethal weapon 4 " ( jet's u . s . debut ) didn't allow .

docs.text: unfortunately , a lot of jet's fights are aided with computer effects that detract from his ability and precision .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: also " romeo must die " must be noted as having the most singularly useless effect ever committed to film , and that is an x-ray effect that appears three times during the course of the film , showing the effect of bone crushing blows on an opponent .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: obviously a homage to the famed x-ray scene from sonny chiba's " streetfighter " , the scenes here are just pointless and interfere with the pacing of the film .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: a fine example of this difference can be found by examining a couple of jackie chan's films . .

docs.text: watch the restaurant fight from the film " rush hour " and notice that the context of the fight , while technically amazing is rather flat ( the framing and cut always do not help ) .
